courses.learning_outcomes:
Students completing this course will achieve a basic understanding that:
1. Sign language enjoys the same linguistic status as spoken language in human interaction;
2. There is a continuum of signing varieties adopted by hearing and deaf individuals in society in relative degrees;
3. Sign language transmission through generations is necessitated by a Deaf Community with members who take sign language as a means of communication;
4. Sign language is acquirable by children, deaf or hearing, and supports their language, cognitive and emotional development.

Students will achieve a basic understanding of:
1. How deaf children access the grammar of natural languages through the auditory/oral and visual-spatial modalities;
2. The complex situations in which deaf children acquire spoken and sign language;
3. Factors surrounding deaf children’s language acquisition such as linguistic input and critical period effects;
4. The acquisition processes of sign or spoken language by deaf children; and
5. Research skills required for investigating deaf children’s language acquisition.

Students completing this course will achieve a basic understanding that:
1. Different modes of interpreting (e.g., sight translation, consecutive interpreting, and simultaneous interpreting) serve different purpose in communication access;
2. Due to the minority status of the Deaf community and development of their service demand, different models of sign language interpreting are developed;
3. Sign language interpreters have to equip themselves with and respond to different demands in the discourse setting;
4. The roles of Deaf interpreters have been serving a broader purpose of language communication and it is also a form of human rights empowerment.

The learning outcomes of this course depend on the specific issues introduced by the course instructors. With the exposure of various topics which are not covered in the regular BMBL Program, students' knowledge and understanding in different areas of sign language studies will be broadened and enhanced.

- to introduce students to a particular area(s) of sign language studies;
- to familiarize students with the literature of that particular area of sign language studies;
- to apply sign linguistics knowledge into the analysis of language-related phenomena.

Students completing this course will have acquired the following skills:
1. How to identify a research topic and defend it to the effect of generating findings that constitute significant insight for resolving a problem in society;
2. How to survey the literature and critically evaluate the observations reported therein for their strengths and limitations;
3. How to develop a bibliography pertaining to the topic, and compile one that complies with certain publication standards;
4. How to generate research questions based on the review of literature; and
5. How to develop an appropriate methodology to tackle the research topic.

Students completing this course will have acquired the following skills:
1. How to present data in a clear and succinct format;
2. How to transcribe and present sign language data, and if necessary, spoken language data, for publication;
3. How to conduct statistics for testing of significance of the hypotheses generated;
4. How to write a formal research report and compile a stylized PPT for oral presentation; and
5. More importantly, how to critically evaluate to what extent the results are applicable to resolving relevant problems in society.

Students completing this course will achieve a basic understanding about:
1. A professional interest must be socially and empirically driven, supported by ongoing research to inform the practice;
2. The backgrounds and missions of different organizations that pursue bimodal bilingualism in their services;
3. How to prepare an application for internship programmes;
4. The necessary process of self-reflection along the development of one’s career path

Students completing this course will have the opportunity to:
Gain practical experience within the bimodal bilingual environment;
Acquire knowledge of the industry in which the service provision is done;
Apply knowledge and skills learned in the classroom in a work setting;
Develop a greater understanding about career options while more clearly defining personal career goals;
Experience the activities and functions of business, welfare, and educational professionals;
Develop and refine oral, signed and written communication skills;
Identify areas for future knowledge and skill development.

courses.course_syllabus:
Students are expected to work for at least 80 hours in the placement organization and set-up meetings with their supervisors. The total meeting hours with their academic supervisor and their organization manager should be added up to approximately 10 hours. Students are responsible for all materials and announcements related to the course. All assignments should be completed and turned in by the deadline. Meetings with the academic supervisor at Chinese University of Hong Kong (CUHK) and the organization manager at your own organization should be arranged regularly. You are expected to present yourself in a professional manner at all times. Additionally, you are representing yourself, the Bimodal Bilingual Studies, the School of Arts and CUHK as an CUHK intern at the organization. Please keep in mind that you are expected to:
1. Arrive at work as scheduled, ready to work, and stay for the agreed upon time;
2. Present yourself in a professional manner at all times, including being appropriately dressed for your workplace;
3. Communicate any concerns with your supervisor and the internship supervisor in a timely manner and respectfully;
4. Demonstrate enthusiasm and interest in what you are doing; ask questions and take initiative as appropriate;
5. Complete and submit assigned tasks by designated timelines. Meet all deadlines;
6. Participate in assigned meetings at work and with the internship coordinator at CUHK;
7. Keep track of and accurately report internship hours worked.
